performed_via_github_app.description:
Amazon Q Developer is a generative AI assistant that enables you to automate code changes and legacy code transformation, all from a GitHub issue. After completing its code changes, Amazon Q Developer generates a pull request for your review. Start with 500 invocations per month of Amazon Q Developer‚Äôs feature development and code review capabilities and 10,000 lines of Java transformations per month. Increase your usage at any time by registering your Amazon Q Developer app installation with your AWS account.

# Feature development

Amazon Q Developer allows you to generate code directly from natural language prompts. You can build new features, debug, refine algorithms by describing your requests and letting Amazon Q Developer perform the tasks. It can help to save time, reduce errors, and improve efficiency with code generation that evolves with your project.

# Code transformation

Amazon Q Developer transforms outdated codebases into scalable, efficient, and maintainable systems. You can update your technology stack, enhance performance, and ensure future compatibility while preserving the core functionality of your existing code. With Amazon Q Developer, you can avoid technical debt and build your applications for long-term implications.

# Code review

With Amazon Q Developer, you can automate code reviews within GitHub. When Amazon Q Developer performs a code review, it analyzes your pull requests, provides feedback on code quality, potential issues, and security concerns. Amazon Q Developer then provides suggestions based on the code review.


# Getting started

1. Select the GitHub repositories that can use Amazon Q Developer and complete the authorization process.
2. Get started using Amazon Q Developer in an issue by adding labels for feature development or code transformation, or by creating a new pull request for code review.

issue.title: "Split alternative pattern" code action

type.name: Feature
type.description: A request, idea, or new functionality

issue.body:
Sometimes code starts out as dealing with 2 patterns in the same way, but then later, something different has to happen for one or all of the cases. It could be nice if the language server provided a code action to split an alternative pattern into individual pattern matches.

Before:

```gleam
case next() {
  Ok(response) -> response
  Error(MissingAccessToken) | Error(MissingRefreshToken) -> unauthorized()
  //  ^ split alternative patterns
}
```

After:

```gleam
case next() {
  Ok(response) -> response
  Error(MissingAccessToken) -> unauthorized()
  Error(MissingRefreshToken) -> unauthorized()
}
```

To consider:
- split The pattern on the selected pipe; That would make it more flexible, but would require more clicks to fully split a pattern.
- Split out only the currently hovered alternative, leaving the rest in place

~ üíú

issue.title: Add a folder filter to channel settings
issue.body:
<!-- Issue description -->

We should make it possible to filter channels by folder in the channel settings UI. Let's try:

- Add a neutral, medium-emphasis button with a folder icon just to the right of the filter box.
- Clicking the icon opens a searchable dropdown with the following options:

---
Any folder <- default option; yellow styling
Uncategorized <- yellow styling; or maybe "unfiled" or some other term, pending [#design > uncategorized channels label](https://chat.zulip.org/#narrow/channel/101-design/topic/uncategorized.20channels.20label/with/2244650)
[list of folders]

---

- When a folder is selected from the dropdown, we could show a different icon to indicate that a selection was made (https://lucide.dev/icons/folder-search ?), and change the button to be brand-color, without displaying which folder is currently selected.


<!-- Link to a message in the chat.zulip.org discussion. Message links will still work even if the topic is renamed or resolved. Link back to this issue from the chat.zulip.org thread. -->

CZO thread

comment.body:
@alya      Implementation Details:
Folder Filter Button:
A neutral, medium-emphasis button with a folder icon would be placed to the right of the existing filter box in the channel settings UI.
Searchable Dropdown Menu:
Clicking this folder icon would reveal a searchable dropdown menu containing filtering options:
"Any folder": This would be the default selection, styled in yellow, and would display all channels regardless of their folder assignment.
"Uncategorized": Also styled in yellow, this option would display channels that have not been assigned to any specific folder. The exact label ("Uncategorized," "not filed," etc.) is subject to design review.
List of Folders: A comprehensive list of all existing folders would be presented, allowing users to select a specific folder to filter channels by.
Nice job with the nested Wrapper Object. This is a complex area that can trip a lot of people up.
